                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d326">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8993: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-31T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 31, 1937—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>331. Your 505, July 27, 1 p.m., first paragraph. The Department has been informed
                    by our Embassy at Peiping that the Senior Commandant at no time received from a
                    Japanese liaison officer information such as is reported in the paragraph under
                    reference, and that according to information received from the British Embassy
                    at Peiping that Embassy telegraphed London a corrected version of that matter in
                    a telegram despatched a few hours after the original message. It is assumed that
                    you were not informed of the receipt by the British Foreign Office of the
                    corrected version.</p>
                <p>The Department suggests that you may care informally to bring the foregoing to
                    the attention of the Foreign Office with comment that the action taken was,
                    fortunately, entirely appropriate.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
